PREDICTING COMPRESSIVE STRENGTH OF CONCRETE | FEATURIZATION | MODEL SELECTION | TUNING

Concrete is the most important material in civil engineering. The concrete compressive strength is a highly nonlinear function of age and ingredients. These ingredients include cement, blast furnace slag, fly ash, water, superplasticizer, coarse aggregate, and fine aggregate.

This modeling efffort uses the concrete mix data provided herewith and tries to predict the strength of high performance concrete using Machine Learning.

OBJECTIVE

Objective is to build a ML model, learning using historical data and modeling for predicting the strength of high performance concrete. Feature Engineering techniques will be used to determine the optimal set of concrete data features

Data Description

The actual concrete compressive strength (MPa) for a given mixture under a specific age (days) was determined from laboratory. Data is in raw form (not scaled). The data has 8 quantitative input variables, and 1 quantitative output variable, and 1030 instances (observations).

Attribute Information

  • Cement : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Blast : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Fly ash : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Water : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Superplasticizer : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Coarse Aggregate : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Fine Aggregate : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Age : day (1~365)
  • Concrete compressive strength measured in MPa

    Profile Report (Observations)

  • The Concrete data set is a multivariate data.

  • There are 1030 Observations/Rows and 9 material Attributes/Columns

  • The dataset contains concrete material mixture setting for age between '1' and '365' days

  • There are no missing values in the dataset

  • There are no negative values in the dataset

  • There are no duplicate rows in the dataset

  • The dataset contains 9 quantitative numeric variables of which are 8 are input varaibles and 'strength' is the target variable.

  • That is there are eight independent variables (cement, slag, ash, water, superplastic, coarseagg, fineagg, age) and one dependent variable (strength).

  • The concrete mix data distribution based on feature 'age' is highly imbalanced. Data contains larger number of observations (almost 42%) for an 'age' of 28 days.

  • Looking at the 5-point summary values across all the features, the scale of some of the attributes are largely different from each other. Hence we will need to do Feature scaling prior to modeling.

    BIVARIATE ANALYSIS OBSERVATIONS

    Form the above analysis of Concrete mix dataset using Scatterplot, Correlation scores and Correlation heatmaps, we can observe the following:

    i) cement vs other independent attributes:

    Cement does not have any significant relation with slag, ash, water, superplatic, coarseagg,fineagg and age. It spread like a cloud and the r value of it w.r.t other variables is almost zero or insignificant.
    However, it is linearly related to Strength and has a positive correlation. It is not a strong predictor though.

    ii) Slag vs other independent attributes:

    Slag does not have any significant relation with ash, water, superplatic, coarseagg,fineagg and age. It almost spread like a cloud adn dispersed and has an insignifcant correlation value.
    It has a positive but weak correlation with Strength and thus a very weak predictor.

    iii) Ash vs other independent attributes:

    Ash does not have any significant relation with water, superplatic, coarseagg,fineagg and age. It's almost spread like a cloud and has an insignifcant correlation value.
    It has a negative and weak correlation with Strength and thus a very weak predictor.

    iv) Water vs other independent attributes:

    Water seems to have a negative linear relationship with superplastic and fineagg. It does not have any significant relationship with other independent atributes. This is true as Superplasticizers allows the reduction of water in the concrete upto the extent of 30% without reducing the workability.
    It has a negative and weak correlation with Strength and thus a very weak predictor.

    v) Superplastic vs other independent attributes:

    Superplastic has a negative linear relationship with water. It does not have any significant relationship with other independent attributes.
    It has a positive but weak correlation with Strength and thus a weak predictor.

    vi) Coarseagg vs other independent attributes:

    Coarseagg is negatively correlated to all other independent attributes but does not have a strong correlation. Its dispersed and spread like a cloud, r-value is insignificant.
    It has a negative but weak correlation with Strength and thus a weak predictor.

    vii) Fineagg vs other independent attributes:

    Fineagg is negatively correlated to all other independent attributes but does not have a strong correlation. Its dispersed and spread like a cloud, r-value is insignificant.
    It has a negative but weak correlation with Strength and thus a weak predictor.

    viii) Age vs other independent attributes:

    Age does not have any relation to any other independent attribute.

    It has a positive but weak correlation with Strength and thus not a very strong predictor.

    Since there is not relationship between the predictor adn target attributes and absence of linearity between indepedent attributes, we will not use the Linear Model, a Quadratic or Higher degree will help instead.

    In [83]:
    # Outlier Imputatuion using Median
#Replacing the outliers by median

for col_name in concrete_df1.columns[:-1]:
    q1 = concrete_df1[col_name].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = concrete_df1[col_name].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3 - q1    
    low = q1-1.5*iqr
    high = q3+1.5*iqr
    concrete_df1.loc[(concrete_df1[col_name] < low) | (concrete_df1[col_name] > high), col_name] = concrete_df1[col_name].median()
